## Finding: Phase 5.5 Alpha Scope Is Critically Under-Specified

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: An alpha release phase owns a unique set of responsibilities that no other phase covers. The 5 current skills (backup_strategy, env_validation, error_tracking, health_checks, qa_playbook) address general infrastructure concerns that any production app needs — they do NOT address the specific lifecycle of an alpha program. First-principles decomposition of what "alpha" means reveals at minimum 12 atomic responsibilities: (1) alpha tester recruitment and onboarding, (2) access-gating (invite-only, allowlist), (3) outage/incident communication to alpha cohort, (4) staged rollout verification (is the alpha cohort receiving features?), (5) crash/panic reporting with session context, (6) performance baseline establishment (what is "normal" before you have beta traffic?), (7) SLA definition for alpha (uptime promises to testers, if any), (8) alpha-specific data policies (can testers trust their data survives?), (9) telemetry/event collection with alpha-specific instrumentation, (10) tester feedback loop (NPS, in-session annotation), (11) alpha exit criteria (what metrics/signals graduate you to beta?), (12) incident escalation procedures specific to alpha context (small cohort, high-trust testers, direct communication lines). None of these are covered by any current skill.
### Proposed Resolution: Multiple new skills needed — see findings below for individual atomic gaps. Umbrella: alpha_program_management skill at P0.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Without alpha program management, graduation from Alpha to Beta (5.75) has no defined criteria. The feedback_system in Phase 5.75 assumes a feedback collection mechanism during beta — but there is no mechanism established in 5.5 to bootstrap alpha tester relationships that would make beta feedback meaningful.

================================================================

## Finding: No Alpha Tester Onboarding or Access Control Skill

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: An alpha is by definition a restricted, invite-only cohort. Phase 5.5 has no skill covering: invite code generation, allowlist management, alpha-specific user registration flow, alpha tester NDA/agreement acknowledgment, cohort size limits, or access revocation. The qa_playbook covers testing procedures but assumes testers already have access. There is no skill describing HOW to get trusted testers into the system in a controlled, auditable way.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill: alpha_access_control — covers invite code system (UUID tokens, time-limited, single-use), allowlist-based registration, alpha-specific onboarding email/page, cohort size caps enforced at registration, and access revocation procedures.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 5.75 (Beta) assumes a larger but still gated audience. The access control patterns established in alpha directly inform beta waitlist and feature_flags (which exists in 5.75 but has no foundation established in 5.5).

================================================================

## Finding: No Outage Communication or Incident Response Skill

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: When production goes down during alpha, there is no skill covering how to communicate with the alpha cohort. Alpha testers are high-trust, vocal users who expect direct communication — not a generic status page. There is no template for "alpha incident notification email," no status page configuration, no communication runbook. The health_checks skill establishes detection; nothing establishes response and communication. The error_tracking skill captures errors in Sentry; nothing translates those errors into human communication to affected users.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill: incident_communication — covers status page setup (statuspage.io, Better Uptime status page, or self-hosted), incident template library (outage start, update, resolution emails), alpha cohort notification mechanism (direct email list or in-app banner), post-mortem template.
### Cross-Phase Impact: This gap persists into Phase 5.75 (Beta) and Phase 6 (Handoff). A team that never learns incident communication during alpha will not have it for beta either.

================================================================

## Finding: No Performance Baseline Establishment

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: Alpha is the first time real users touch real infrastructure. There is no skill covering the establishment of performance baselines: p50/p95/p99 latency, request throughput, error rates, DB query times, memory/CPU utilization under real load. Without a documented baseline from alpha, the team has no reference point to detect regressions during beta scaling. The health_checks skill monitors binary up/down. The error_tracking skill tracks exceptions. Neither establishes quantitative performance norms.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill: performance_baseline — covers APM setup (Datadog, New Relic, or self-hosted OpenTelemetry), key metric definition (latency percentiles, throughput, Apdex score), baseline capture procedure during alpha week 1, alert threshold derivation from baseline, documentation template for baseline report.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 5.75 (Beta) adds product_analytics but lacks backend performance context. Without a Phase 5.5 baseline, you cannot tell if Beta traffic is causing degradation relative to Alpha performance.

