## Finding: error_tracking Depth Grade — ADEQUATE (missing alpha-specific instrumentation)

### Gap Type: SHALLOW_COVERAGE
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: error_tracking covers Sentry integration across NestJS, React, and Next.js with scrubbing, source maps, release tracking, and alerts. This is the right foundation. However, it is shallow in three alpha-specific areas: (1) No guidance on Sentry tagging errors with alpha cohort identifiers (e.g., `Sentry.setTag('cohort', 'alpha-v1')`) so alpha errors are filterable from future beta/production noise in the same project. (2) No session replay configuration guidance beyond the default `maskAllText: true` — during alpha, session replay is a critical debugging tool and the privacy/consent tradeoff needs to be addressed explicitly (alpha testers sign up knowing they are testing, so replay can be more permissive). (3) tracesSampleRate defaults to 0.2 in production — during alpha with low traffic, 1.0 is appropriate to capture every transaction for baseline establishment. This conflicts with the performance_baseline gap identified in Loop 1.
### Proposed Resolution: Add alpha-specific Sentry configuration section: cohort tagging, session replay consent for alpha testers, and elevated tracesSampleRate during alpha period.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Without alpha cohort tagging, errors from alpha will pollute beta error streams in the same Sentry project, making triage harder.

