## Finding: Failure Mode — Different Stack: health_checks Fails for Serverless Deployments

### Gap Type: FAILURE_MODE_UNCOVERED
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: health_checks is built entirely around NestJS + Terminus + persistent process model (liveness/readiness probes, startup grace period, AppReadinessService). If the project being alpha-tested is deployed serverlessly (Vercel Functions, AWS Lambda, Cloudflare Workers), the entire health check architecture is inappropriate: there is no persistent process to probe, no memory RSs check possible, no disk usage check, and liveness/readiness probes do not apply. The skill does not acknowledge this failure mode or provide an alternative for serverless stacks. A team with a Next.js API routes deployment would apply this skill and build infrastructure that does nothing useful.
### Proposed Resolution: Add a "Serverless Health Checks" section to health_checks: synthetic health check pattern (external uptime monitor pings an edge function, function calls DB), cold start time monitoring, serverless-specific metrics (invocation error rate, duration p99, concurrent executions).
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 5.75 product_analytics will track frontend metrics regardless of stack. Backend health monitoring for serverless needs to be established in Phase 5.5.

================================================================

## Finding: Failure Mode — Team Size Change: qa_playbook Breaks at 1-Person Team

### Gap Type: FAILURE_MODE_UNCOVERED
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: qa_playbook assumes a team where a dedicated QA person runs through test cases, fills in pass/fail tables, and files bug reports. For a solo founder or 2-person team in alpha (the most common scenario for early-stage products), this process is unworkable: the same person writing code is running QA, the test cases feel like bureaucratic overhead, and the structured table format is not maintained. The skill has no "solo/small team" adaptation: abbreviated smoke tests, automated test coverage as substitute for manual test cases in certain sections, or a lighter-weight tracking mechanism (GitHub Issues labels vs. a table).
### Proposed Resolution: Add a "Solo / Small Team Mode" section to qa_playbook: a condensed 20-item essential-only checklist derived from the full test suite, guidance on which sections can be replaced by automated tests, and a simpler bug tracking approach (GitHub Issues with labels vs. a table).
### Cross-Phase Impact: If the qa_playbook is abandoned because it is too heavyweight for a small team, the team enters Phase 5.75 Beta with no structured QA process — the feedback_system catches issues reactively, not proactively.

