## Finding: Failure Mode — Compliance Regime Change: backup_strategy Is Inadequate for HIPAA/PCI

### Gap Type: FAILURE_MODE_UNCOVERED
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: backup_strategy covers standard data protection (encrypted at rest, S3 lifecycle, access control). It mentions GDPR data export. It does NOT address compliance-specific backup requirements: HIPAA requires 6-year retention of PHI backups (vs. the 12-month maximum in the skill), PCI DSS requires cardholder data backups to be encrypted with keys stored separately (vs. the SSE-AES256 approach that stores keys in AWS), SOC 2 requires documented backup procedures with access logs. A healthcare or fintech alpha that follows this skill verbatim would fail their first compliance audit. The skill is also PostgreSQL-specific — teams using MySQL, MongoDB, or cloud-specific databases (DynamoDB, Firestore) have no coverage.
### Proposed Resolution: Add compliance-regime callout boxes to backup_strategy: HIPAA retention note, PCI key management note, SOC 2 audit log note. Add a non-PostgreSQL section or at minimum a note directing teams to provider-specific backup documentation.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Compliance gaps found during beta (5.75) or handoff (Phase 6) are far more expensive to fix than gaps caught during alpha (5.5). The alpha phase is the right time to establish compliant backup practices.

