## Finding: Industry Standard Deviation — DORA Metrics Not Mentioned

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: DORA (DevOps Research and Assessment) defines four key metrics for software delivery performance: Deployment Frequency, Lead Time for Changes, Change Failure Rate, and Mean Time to Restore. These metrics are the industry standard for measuring DevOps maturity. During alpha, teams should establish baseline DORA measurements — not to achieve elite performance, but to have a reference point for improvement. Phase 5.5 has no skill mentioning DORA metrics. The health_checks skill mentions uptime monitoring. The ci_cd_pipeline in Phase 5 covers deployment frequency implicitly. But no skill in 5.5 aggregates these into DORA reporting. Teams that never measure DORA metrics during alpha/beta cannot quantify their engineering effectiveness for investors, boards, or their own improvement.
### Proposed Resolution: Add DORA metrics tracking section to either an alpha_program_management skill or as an addition to health_checks: define the four metrics, provide lightweight tracking approaches (GitHub Actions run data, deployment timestamps, incident duration logs), and recommend tools (LinearB, Sleuth, or custom dashboards).
### Cross-Phase Impact: DORA metrics tracked from alpha become the baseline for continuous improvement through beta (5.75), handoff (6), and maintenance (7). Establishing them in 5.5 is the right time.

================================================================

## Finding: Industry Standard Deviation — SRE Error Budget Concept Absent

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: Google's Site Reliability Engineering practices (widely adopted as industry standard) define the error budget concept: the acceptable amount of unreliability based on an SLO. For alpha with a target 99% uptime SLO, the error budget is 1% of time = ~7.2 hours/month of acceptable downtime. This concept directly answers "should we delay this risky migration?" (check error budget remaining) and "how much alpha testing can we do before we owe tester uptime?" None of Phase 5.5's skills use error budget terminology or establish SLOs as a first-class concept. The health_checks skill monitors health but never defines an acceptable health threshold as an SLO. The backup_strategy defines RPO/RTO which are disaster recovery concepts but not availability SLOs.
### Proposed Resolution: Add SLO/error budget section to health_checks or a new skill: define SLO for alpha (99% or 95%), calculate error budget, provide a simple error budget burn rate dashboard (Grafana or Datadog template), and decision framework for "is the error budget depleted? → freeze risky changes."
### Cross-Phase Impact: SLO/error budget discipline is an industry standard for Phase 6 (Handoff) SLA negotiations with customers. Establishing the concept in Phase 5.5 is essential for organizational maturity.

================================================================

## Finding: Industry Standard Deviation — OWASP Application Security Testing Not Integrated into QA

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: OWASP defines the Application Security Verification Standard (ASVS) and provides the OWASP Testing Guide as the industry standard for security testing. Phase 5.5's qa_playbook has a "Security Spot-Check" section (TC-SEC-001 through TC-SEC-005) covering auth bypass, IDOR, SQL injection, sensitive data in URL, and HTTPS enforcement. This is a surface-level security check — it misses OWASP ASVS Level 1 items including: CSRF protection verification, HTTP security header validation (Content-Security-Policy, X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options), cookie security flags (Secure, HttpOnly, SameSite), session fixation, open redirect vulnerabilities, and mass assignment vulnerabilities. An alpha that ships without these checks will have these vulnerabilities exposed to real users.
### Proposed Resolution: Extend qa_playbook Security section with OWASP ASVS Level 1 test cases (the minimum standard for any Internet-facing application). Alternatively, create a dedicated alpha_security_checklist skill that maps to OWASP ASVS Level 1 requirements with specific test steps.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (Secure) presumably covers security hardening, but Phase 5.5 needs a security verification checkpoint specific to alpha deployment. OWASP compliance in alpha prevents embarrassing vulnerability disclosures during beta's broader exposure.

================================================================

## Finding: Industry Standard Deviation — No Structured Post-Incident Review Process

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: Industry SRE practice (Google SRE Book, PagerDuty Incident Response, Atlassian Incident Management Guide) mandates post-incident reviews (post-mortems) for any significant outage. The industry standard format includes: timeline, contributing factors, impact assessment, action items with owners and due dates, and a blameless culture statement. Phase 5.5 has no skill covering post-incident review. The incident_communication gap (identified in Loop 1) addresses communicating during an incident; a post-mortem skill addresses learning from it. During alpha, every incident is a learning opportunity that should be documented and addressed before beta.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill: post_incident_review — covers the blameless post-mortem template, timeline reconstruction procedure, impact quantification method, action item tracking, and the follow-through mechanism to verify action items were completed before beta launch.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Post-incident review discipline in alpha is the mechanism for continuously improving the system before the higher-stakes beta phase. Teams that skip post-mortems in alpha repeatedly encounter the same incidents in beta.

================================================================

## Finding: Industry Standard Deviation — ISO 27001 / SOC 2 Data Handling Requirements

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: ISO 27001 and SOC 2 Type II are the industry standard security certifications for SaaS companies. Both require: access control logging (who accessed what data when), change management procedures (documented approval for changes to production), incident response plans (formalized, not ad-hoc), and vendor risk assessment (for third-party services like Sentry, Supabase, AWS). Phase 5.5 has none of these. If the alpha product intends to pursue SOC 2 certification (which is increasingly required by enterprise customers), the foundation must be laid during alpha: establishing access logging, formalizing change management, and documenting the vendor list. Starting SOC 2 readiness in Phase 5.5 means certification is achievable by Phase 6 (Handoff). Starting in Phase 6 means a 12-18 month delay.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill: compliance_foundation — covers SOC 2/ISO 27001 readiness checklist for alpha stage, access logging setup (who deploys, who accesses production DB), change management log template, vendor inventory creation, and a recommended timeline for certification pursuit.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Compliance foundation established in Phase 5.5 Alpha directly unlocks enterprise sales in Phase 6 (Handoff). This is a high-leverage investment.

